// ATPG D-algorithm example for AND gate
// Gate: Y = A & B
// Fault: SA0 on Y

// Step 1: Activate fault
// Need Y=1 fault-free: set A=1, B=1
// Now Y=D (fault-free=1, faulty=0)

// Step 2: Propagate D to primary output
// Y is directly observable → propagation complete
// Test vector: A=1, B=1, expect Y=1 (fault-free)
//              A=1, B=1, get   Y=0 (faulty → detected!)

// ATPG with scan chain:
// Fault: SA0 on internal flop Q3
// 1. Initialize: shift in values so Q3 gets activated
// 2. Capture: clock once (SE=0), observe Q3 output
// 3. Shift out: read TDO, compare to expected

// STIL format (Standard Test Interface Language)
// Pattern {Force A 1; Force B 1; Measure Y H;}
// H = expect logic high
// L = expect logic low
// X = don't care

// TetraMAX command (industry ATPG tool):
// run_atpg -effort high
// report_statistics   → shows coverage
// write_patterns test.stil -format stil

// Circuit: Y = (A & B) | C
// Gate structure:
//   G1: w1 = A & B  (AND)
//   G2: Y  = w1 | C (OR)

// TARGET: Detect SA0 on w1

// Step 1: ACTIVATE
// SA0 on w1: fault-free w1=1 needed
// Need A=1 AND B=1
// Set A=1, B=1 → w1=D (1 FF, 0 faulty)

// Step 2: PROPAGATE through G2 (OR gate)
// w1=D, need C=0 to propagate D
// OR(D, 0) = D → Y=D ✓ observable!

// Step 3: JUSTIFY (backward implication)
// A=1 ← primary input ✓
// B=1 ← primary input ✓
// C=0 ← primary input ✓
// All inputs justified!

// FINAL TEST VECTOR:
// A=1, B=1, C=0
// Expected Y = 1 (fault-free)
// Faulty Y   = 0 (w1 stuck at 0)
// FAULT DETECTED ✓

// Fault coverage impact:
// This one vector detects:
// - w1 SA0, A SA0 (same activation)
// - Y SA0 (if Y=0 expected 1)
// Multiple faults detected per vector = efficient!

