// INTERVIEW REFERENCE: Fault Coverage Formula
// Coverage = (Detected + Possibly_Detected) /
//            (Total_Faults - Undetectable_Faults)
// Example: 990 detected, 5 PD, 8 undetect, total 1000
// Coverage = (990+5) / (1000-8) = 995/992 = 100.3%
// → Report as 100% (PD counted as detected)

// Real example:
// Total: 100,000
// Detected: 98,500
// PD: 700
// Undetectable: 300
// Coverage = (98500+700)/(100000-300) = 99,200/99,700 = 99.5%

// Interview Q1: Why SE=1 shift, SE=0 capture?
// SE=1: flops form shift register, TDI data loads
// SE=0: flops operate functionally (D input used)
// Capture in functional mode = observing real circuit behavior
// If SE=1 during capture, no functional logic evaluated!

// Interview Q2: Untestable fault example
// Gate: Y = A & (!A)  → always 0 (redundant logic)
// SA1 on Y: Y=1 is impossible even fault-free
// → Cannot create test that distinguishes fault from fault-free
// Redundant logic creates untestable faults

// Interview Q3: Why can't scan test SRAM?
// SRAM cell: 6T cross-coupled inverters + access transistors
// These are NOT standard scan flip-flops
// Scan chain only connects D flip-flops in the design
// SRAM internal array is completely invisible to scan
// → Need MBIST with march algorithm

// Interview Q4: X propagation causes and fixes
// Cause 1: Uninitialized flip-flops (no reset before shift)
// Cause 2: Async resets not controlled (X on reset path)
// Cause 3: Multidriven nets (short circuit)
// Fix: Always reset before shift, make reset controllable

// Interview Q5: LBIST vs MBIST
